docs.abstract: Putting on a Super Bowl halftime show is always a mammoth undertaking. The pandemic introduces many more logistical puzzles.
docs.snippet: Putting on a Super Bowl halftime show is always a mammoth undertaking. The pandemic introduces many more logistical puzzles.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the Weeknd headlines the Super Bowl halftime show on Sunday, the stage will be in the stands, not on the field, to simplify the transition from game to performance. In the days leading up to the event, workers have visited a tent outside Raymond James Stadium in Tampa, Fla., to receive nasal swabs for Covid-19 tests. And though a smaller crew is putting on the show this year, the bathroom trailers have been going through three times as much water as usual — because of all that hand-washing.

headline.main: Behind the Weeknd’s Halftime Show: Nasal Swabs and Backup Plans

docs.abstract: The artist Desmond Lewis brings the glow of professional fireworks to under-resourced communities in the South.
docs.snippet: The artist Desmond Lewis brings the glow of professional fireworks to under-resourced communities in the South.
docs.lead_paragraph: GREENWOOD, Miss. — On Saturday night, June 18, the Memphis-based artist Desmond Lewis was in a public park unloading cakes — bundles of fireworks connected by a high-speed fuse — from a pickup truck. On the other side of a nearby tree line waited about 150 expectant onlookers for the Juneteenth celebration in the city that is heralded as “the cotton capital of the world.”

docs.abstract: These two canonical dance artists, both now 70, share a willingness to take on weighty issues.
docs.snippet: These two canonical dance artists, both now 70, share a willingness to take on weighty issues.
docs.lead_paragraph: Eiko Otake and Bill T. Jones are two celebrated dance artists with different styles, temperaments and cultural backgrounds. What they have in common is their willingness — hunger, really — to take on weighty issues. Otake has been illuminating the environmental damage caused by nuclear accidents. Jones is intimately connected to the struggle against racism.

headline.main: Bill T. Jones and Eiko Otake: Opposites Guided by ‘Too-Much-Ness’

docs.abstract: Several institutions are preparing to reopen with an awareness of a new mission as people struggle with loss and unrest.
docs.snippet: Several institutions are preparing to reopen with an awareness of a new mission as people struggle with loss and unrest.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the instructor asked him to describe his life in two words, Walter Enriquez chose carefully: fear and violence. He had spent decades as a policeman in Peru during the bloodiest days of armed conflict between government forces and guerrilla fighters that killed nearly 70,000 people. But he said that nothing could have prepared him for the extreme isolation and loneliness that come with quarantine. Having lost a handful of his friends and neighbors to the coronavirus pandemic, the 75-year-old retiree has turned toward art therapy programs offered by the Queens Museum to improve his mental health.

headline.main: Museums Embrace Art Therapy Techniques for Unsettled Times
